**Creating an HTTPS POST Request in Node.js**

You can use the `https` module in Node.js to create an HTTPS POST request. Here is a code snippet that demonstrates how to do this:

```javascript
const https = require('https');

// URL to send the request to
const url = 'https://httpbin.org/post';

// Data to send with the request
const data = { 
  name: 'John Doe', 
  age: 30 
};

// Creating the options
const options = {
  hostname: 'httpbin.org',
  port: 80,
  path: '/post',
  method: 'POST',
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
  },
  json: data
};

// Creating the request
const req = https.request(options, res => {
  console.log(`Encoded data: ${JSON.stringify(res.headers)}`);
  res.on('data', (d) => {
    process.stdout.write(d);
  });
});

// Closing the request
req.on('error', error => {
  console.error(error);
});

// Sending the request
req.end();
```

This code sends a JSON object to the specified URL. When you run this code, it will output the contents of the response and log any errors.

**Note:** It's recommended to use the `https` module's built-in methods (`request()` and `get()`), as shown above, instead of using the older `https.get()` and `https.post()` methods. The `request()` method can handle more complex requests like HTTP/2, and it's generally easier to work with.

If you're using a modern Edge or Internet Explorer, make sure to target at least Edge 18 or IE 11 to get the `request()` and `end()` functions.
